worship. A Garland of Forgotten Goddesses conveys the diversity of this tradition by bringing together a fresh array of captivating and largely overlooked Hindu goddess tales from different regions. As the first such anthology of goddess narratives in translation, this collection highlights a range of sources from ancient myths to modern lore. The goddesses featured here battle demons, perform miracles, and grant rare Tantric visions to their devotees. Each translation is paired with a short essay that explains the goddess's historical and social context, elucidating the ways religion adapts to changing times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aHindu goddesses. 0aHinduismxDoctrines. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh1 aBirkenholtz, Jessica Vantine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrussel, Noor van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinnell, Darry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolovkova, Anna A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatley, Shaman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Thomas M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasek Ariati, Ni Wayan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaul, R. Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSerbaeva, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimmons, Caleb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlouber, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlouber, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator